  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Letting Health Insurance Lapse</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Maintaining adequate health insurance is a visa condition. If your policy expires or you cancel it, you're in breach. This can affect future visa applications and potentially lead to visa cancellation. Set up auto-renewal.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Medicare is Enough</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Even if you're from an RHCA country and can access Medicare, you still need private health insurance for visa compliance. Medicare supplements your coverage but doesn't satisfy the visa requirement.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Checking Occupation List</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Occupation lists change regularly. Confirm your specific ANZSCO code is on MLTSSL (for medium-term/PR pathway) or STSOL (short-term) before committing. An occupation removed from lists can derail plans.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Skills Assessment Time</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Skills assessments can take 4-12 weeks, and some require additional qualifications or English tests. Start immediately once you have a job offer. Don't assume your qualifications will be automatically recognized.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Working for Wrong Employer</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">TSS 482 is tied to your sponsoring employer. You can't legally work for a different employer without changing your visa. If you want to change jobs, the new employer must become your sponsor.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Australia -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Australia</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Australia has a high-quality healthcare system combining public Medicare and private insurance. As a TSS 482 holder, your access depends on your nationality and insurance choices. Even with Medicare access, private insurance is required for visa compliance.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Medicare for RHCA Countries</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      If you're from an RHCA country (UK, Ireland, NZ, etc.), you can access Medicare for "immediately necessary" treatment. This includes:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Bulk-billed GPs:</strong> Free visits at participating doctors</li>
      <li><strong>Public hospitals:</strong> Free emergency and inpatient care</li>
      <li><strong>PBS medications:</strong> Subsidized prescription medicines</li>
      <li><strong>Medicare rebates:</strong> Partial refund on specialist visits</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>RHCA limitations:</strong> Medicare through RHCA doesn't cover elective procedures, private hospitals, dental, optical, or ambulance in most states. It's not a full replacement for comprehensive health cover.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Using Private Health Insurance</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Hospital Cover</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Private insurance covers treatment in private hospitals, choice of doctor, and shorter wait times for elective surgery. In the public system, you take whoever's available with longer waits.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Extras Cover</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Add extras cover for dental, optical, physiotherapy, and other services not covered by Medicare. Annual limits apply—check policy details.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ambulance Cover</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Ambulance isn't covered by Medicare in most states (only Tasmania and Queensland). Private insurance typically includes ambulance cover—essential given Australian distances.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Waiting Periods</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Australian private health insurance has mandatory waiting periods:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>2 months:</strong> General treatments, psychiatric services</li>
      <li><strong>6 months:</strong> Rehabilitation, palliative care</li>
      <li><strong>12 months:</strong> Pre-existing conditions, pregnancy, assisted reproduction</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Plan ahead for pregnancy:</strong> Maternity coverage has a 12-month waiting period. If you're planning to start a family in Australia, arrange insurance at least a year before conception to have coverage when needed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need private health insurance if I have Medicare access?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Private health insurance is a visa condition regardless of Medicare eligibility. RHCA-based Medicare access doesn't satisfy the requirement. You must maintain private cover for the duration of your visa.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I switch employers on a TSS 482?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, but the new employer must become your sponsor and lodge a new nomination. You'll need to apply for a new visa or have your existing visa transferred. You cannot work for the new employer until the process is complete.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the pathway to permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Medium-term stream TSS 482 holders can apply for Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS 186) visa after 3 years with the same employer. This is a direct permanent residence visa. Short-term stream doesn't have this pathway.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family work and study?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Dependents (spouse/de facto partner, children) on TSS 482 secondary visas have full work and study rights. They also need their own health insurance. Children can attend government schools (may involve fees depending on state).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if I lose my job?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You have 60 days to find a new sponsor or apply for a different visa. During this period, your visa remains valid. If you can't find new sponsorship, you'll need to leave Australia or switch to another visa type (e.g., tourist visa for a short period).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is travel insurance enough for the visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Travel insurance doesn't meet the "adequate health insurance" requirement. You need OVHC (Overseas Visitors Health Cover) from an Australian provider or comprehensive international health insurance that covers hospitalization and medical treatment in Australia.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The TSS 482 visa offers a solid pathway for skilled workers to live and work in Australia, with the medium-term stream providing a clear route to permanent residence. The mandatory health insurance requirement, while an added cost, ensures you have quality healthcare access in a country with excellent medical facilities.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For visa compliance, Australian OVHC providers (Bupa, Medibank, NIB) are the safest choice—they're designed specifically for working visa holders and widely accepted. If you're from an RHCA country, you'll have Medicare as a bonus, but still need the private cover for visa purposes.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The higher salary threshold ($73,150 from July 2024) and skills assessment requirements mean more preparation, but Australia's quality of life, working conditions, and PR pathway make it worth the effort for many skilled professionals.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        The TSS 482 visa requires mandatory private health insurance—this is non-negotiable and must be maintained throughout your stay. Choose Australian OVHC for guaranteed visa compliance, and supplement with Medicare if you're from an RHCA country. Start skills assessment and insurance arrangements early for a smooth application.
